<paragraph blockId="9.[236,684,755,816]" box="[385,535,791,816]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[385,535,791,816]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
(
<figureCitation box="[392,527,791,816]" captionStart-0="FIGURE" captionStart-1="FIGURE" captionStartId-0="10.[159,171,1792,1811]" captionStartId-1="11.[159,171,1740,1759]" captionTargetBox-0="[329,1264,429,1708]" captionTargetBox-1="[334,1271,437,1672]" captionTargetId-0="figure-4@10.[242,1345,403,1760]" captionTargetId-1="figure-4@11.[242,1345,427,1708]" captionTargetPageId-0="10" captionTargetPageId-1="11" captionText-0="FIGURE 5: Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp.: A – dorsal view; B – ventral view, legs, subcapitular setae and palps not shown; C – lateral view of prodorsum, legs and gnathosoma not shown; D – sensillus. Scale bar (A+C) 100 µm, scale bar (D) 20 µm." captionText-1="FIGURE 6: Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp.: A – subcapitulum, left half; B – palptarsus; C – anterior part of chelicera; D – tutorium and epimeral seta 4c; E – genital plate, right; F – anal plate, right; G – leg tarsus I, right, paraxial view. Scale bars (A, C, F, G) 20 µm, scale bar (B, D, E) 10 µm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4667211" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4667213" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/4667211/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/4667213/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Figures 5-6</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[159,762,845,1948]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Diagnosis — Body size 448 – 498 x 265 – 282. Sensilli clavate. Interlamellar setae longer than all prodorsal setae. Notogaster with 10 pairs of thin, smooth notogastral setae. Aggenital setae present.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[159,762,845,1948]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
Measurements — Body length 498 (
<typeStatus box="[641,749,992,1016]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">holotype</typeStatus>
), 448 – 498 (mean 471; five 
<typeStatus box="[491,610,1027,1051]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">paratypes</typeStatus>
); notogaster width 282 (
<typeStatus box="[303,411,1062,1086]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">holotype</typeStatus>
), 265 – 282 (mean 272; five 
<typeStatus box="[159,279,1097,1121]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">paratypes</typeStatus>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[159,762,845,1948]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
Integument — (
<figureCitation box="[411,534,1139,1163]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="10.[159,171,1792,1811]" captionTargetBox="[329,1264,429,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-4@10.[242,1345,403,1760]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5: Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp.: A – dorsal view; B – ventral view, legs, subcapitular setae and palps not shown; C – lateral view of prodorsum, legs and gnathosoma not shown; D – sensillus. Scale bar (A+C) 100 µm, scale bar (D) 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4667211" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4667211/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Figures 5</figureCitation>
A-C). Body color brown. Body surface smooth. Posterior part of notogaster and epimeral region with irregular muscle sigilla.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[159,762,845,1948]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
Prodorsum — (
<figureCitation box="[399,629,1286,1310]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="10.[159,171,1792,1811]" captionTargetBox="[329,1264,429,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-4@10.[242,1345,403,1760]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5: Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp.: A – dorsal view; B – ventral view, legs, subcapitular setae and palps not shown; C – lateral view of prodorsum, legs and gnathosoma not shown; D – sensillus. Scale bar (A+C) 100 µm, scale bar (D) 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4667211" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4667211/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Figures 5A, C, D</figureCitation>
). Rostrum rounded in dorsal view. Lamellae located dorsolaterally, little longer than half of prodorsum (see in lateral view), without cusps. Translamella absent, but rudimentary parts present nearly to lamellae. Prolamellar and sublamellar lines present. Sublamellar porose areas (
<emphasis box="[424,451,1497,1521]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Al</emphasis>
) round, small (6 – 8). Rostral (53 – 65), lamellar (90 – 102) and interlamellar (164 – 172) setae setiform, barbed. Lamellar setae inserted on the distal part of lamellae. Sensilli (77 – 82) clavate, its head slightly barbed. Exobothridial setae (2 – 4) minute, thin, smooth. Pedotecta I and II typical for genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[159,762,845,1948]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
Notogaster — (
<figureCitation box="[384,557,1749,1773]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="10.[159,171,1792,1811]" captionTargetBox="[329,1264,429,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-4@10.[242,1345,403,1760]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5: Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp.: A – dorsal view; B – ventral view, legs, subcapitular setae and palps not shown; C – lateral view of prodorsum, legs and gnathosoma not shown; D – sensillus. Scale bar (A+C) 100 µm, scale bar (D) 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4667211" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4667211/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Figures 5A, C</figureCitation>
). Anterio-medial part straight or weakly convex. Ten pairs of short (24 – 36), smooth notogastral setae present. Four pairs of sacculi (
<emphasis box="[358,385,1855,1878]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Sa</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[402,430,1854,1878]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">S1</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[447,474,1854,1878]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">S2</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[492,519,1854,1878]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">S3</emphasis>
) small. Lyrifissures and opisthonotal gland openings in typical arrangement of the family.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[826,1429,311,1949]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
Gnathosoma — (
<figureCitation box="[1064,1174,311,335]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="11.[159,171,1740,1759]" captionTargetBox="[334,1271,437,1672]" captionTargetId="figure-4@11.[242,1345,427,1708]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6: Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp.: A – subcapitulum, left half; B – palptarsus; C – anterior part of chelicera; D – tutorium and epimeral seta 4c; E – genital plate, right; F – anal plate, right; G – leg tarsus I, right, paraxial view. Scale bars (A, C, F, G) 20 µm, scale bar (B, D, E) 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4667213" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4667213/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Figures 6</figureCitation>
A-C). Typical for 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Scheloribatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Scheloribatidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ermilov S. G. &amp; Rybalov L. B. &amp; Franke K." box="[979,1197,346,370]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" pagination="311 - 322" refId="ref6060" refString="Ermilov S. G., Rybalov L. B., Franke K. 2011 - Ethiopian oribatid mites of the family Scheloribatidae (Acari: Oribatida) - Afr. Inverteb., 52 (2): 311 - 322." type="journal article" year="2011">
Ermilov 
<emphasis box="[1082,1133,346,370]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ermilov S. G. &amp; Kaloez S." pageId="9" pageNumber="119" pagination="773 - 787" refId="ref5962" refString="Ermilov S. G., Kaloez S. 2012 e - A new subgenus and three new species of oribatid mites of the family Scheloribatidae (Acari: Oribatida) from Ecuador - Ann. Zool., 63 (4): 773 - 787." type="journal article" year="2012">Ermilov and Kaloez 2012e</bibRefCitation>
). Subcapitulum longer than wide: 94 – 102 x 65 – 69. Subcapitular setae setiform; 
<emphasis box="[1302,1315,416,440]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">h</emphasis>
(24 – 28) and 
<emphasis box="[880,892,452,475]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">a</emphasis>
(16 – 20) slightly barbed, thicker than 
<emphasis box="[1363,1384,452,475]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">m</emphasis>
(16 – 20). Two pairs of adoral setae (10 – 12) setiform, barbed. Palps (length 61) with setation 0-2- 1-3-9(+1ω). Solenidion attached with eupathidium. Chelicerae (length 102) with two setiform, barbed setae; 
<emphasis box="[902,938,626,650]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">cha</emphasis>
(49) longer than 
<emphasis box="[1147,1183,626,650]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">chb</emphasis>
(20). Trägårdh’s organ distinct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[826,1429,311,1949]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
Epimeral region — (
<figureCitation box="[1114,1246,706,731]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="10.[159,171,1792,1811]" captionTargetBox="[329,1264,429,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-4@10.[242,1345,403,1760]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5: Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp.: A – dorsal view; B – ventral view, legs, subcapitular setae and palps not shown; C – lateral view of prodorsum, legs and gnathosoma not shown; D – sensillus. Scale bar (A+C) 100 µm, scale bar (D) 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4667211" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4667211/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Figures 5B</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[1261,1297,707,731]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="11.[159,171,1740,1759]" captionTargetBox="[334,1271,437,1672]" captionTargetId="figure-4@11.[242,1345,427,1708]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6: Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp.: A – subcapitulum, left half; B – palptarsus; C – anterior part of chelicera; D – tutorium and epimeral seta 4c; E – genital plate, right; F – anal plate, right; G – leg tarsus I, right, paraxial view. Scale bars (A, C, F, G) 20 µm, scale bar (B, D, E) 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4667213" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4667213/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">6D</figureCitation>
). Epimeral setal formula: 3-1-3-3. Setae setiform, smooth. Lengths of setae: 
<emphasis box="[1043,1068,777,801]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">1a</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[1085,1111,777,801]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">2a</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[1128,1153,777,801]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">3a</emphasis>
8 – 10; others 16 – 20. Discidia triangular, blunt-ended.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[826,1429,311,1949]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
Anogenital region — (
<figureCitation box="[1138,1269,857,881]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="10.[159,171,1792,1811]" captionTargetBox="[329,1264,429,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-4@10.[242,1345,403,1760]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 5: Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp.: A – dorsal view; B – ventral view, legs, subcapitular setae and palps not shown; C – lateral view of prodorsum, legs and gnathosoma not shown; D – sensillus. Scale bar (A+C) 100 µm, scale bar (D) 20 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4667211" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4667211/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Figures 5B</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[1284,1350,857,881]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="11.[159,171,1740,1759]" captionTargetBox="[334,1271,437,1672]" captionTargetId="figure-4@11.[242,1345,427,1708]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6: Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp.: A – subcapitulum, left half; B – palptarsus; C – anterior part of chelicera; D – tutorium and epimeral seta 4c; E – genital plate, right; F – anal plate, right; G – leg tarsus I, right, paraxial view. Scale bars (A, C, F, G) 20 µm, scale bar (B, D, E) 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4667213" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4667213/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">6E, F</figureCitation>
). Four pairs of genital (
<emphasis box="[1015,1028,893,916]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">g</emphasis>
<subScript attach="left" box="[1028,1037,902,919]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">1</subScript>
, 20 – 24; 
<emphasis box="[1142,1155,893,916]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">g</emphasis>
<subScript attach="left" box="[1155,1164,902,919]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">2</subScript>
- 
<emphasis box="[1174,1187,893,916]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">g</emphasis>
<subScript attach="left" box="[1188,1197,902,919]" fontSize="7" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">4</subScript>
14 – 16), one pair of aggenital (12), two pairs of anal (12 – 16) and three pairs of adanal (20) setae setiform, smooth. Lyrifissures 
<emphasis box="[894,926,997,1021]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">iad</emphasis>
located in paranal position.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[826,1429,311,1949]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">
Legs — (
<figureCitation box="[969,1091,1042,1066]" captionStart="FIGURE" captionStartId="11.[159,171,1740,1759]" captionTargetBox="[334,1271,437,1672]" captionTargetId="figure-4@11.[242,1345,427,1708]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 6: Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp.: A – subcapitulum, left half; B – palptarsus; C – anterior part of chelicera; D – tutorium and epimeral seta 4c; E – genital plate, right; F – anal plate, right; G – leg tarsus I, right, paraxial view. Scale bars (A, C, F, G) 20 µm, scale bar (B, D, E) 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4667213" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4667213/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Figure 6G</figureCitation>
). Typical for 
<taxonomicName box="[1248,1429,1042,1066]" class="Arachnida" family="Scheloribatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Scheloribatidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ermilov S. G. &amp; Rybalov L. B. &amp; Franke K." box="[834,1081,1077,1102]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" pagination="311 - 322" refId="ref6060" refString="Ermilov S. G., Rybalov L. B., Franke K. 2011 - Ethiopian oribatid mites of the family Scheloribatidae (Acari: Oribatida) - Afr. Inverteb., 52 (2): 311 - 322." type="journal article" year="2011">
Ermilov 
<emphasis box="[942,1000,1077,1101]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="119">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ermilov S. G. &amp; Kaloez S." box="[1100,1418,1077,1102]" pageId="9" pageNumber="119" pagination="773 - 787" refId="ref5962" refString="Ermilov S. G., Kaloez S. 2012 e - A new subgenus and three new species of oribatid mites of the family Scheloribatidae (Acari: Oribatida) from Ecuador - Ann. Zool., 63 (4): 773 - 787." type="journal article" year="2012">Ermilov and Kaloez 2012e</bibRefCitation>
). Claw of each tarsus smooth. Homology of setae and solenidia indicated in 
<tableCitation box="[1089,1173,1148,1172]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="12.[446,459,308,327]" captionText="TABLE 3: Leg setation and solenidia of Monoschelobates hemileiformis n. sp." pageId="9" pageNumber="119">Table 3</tableCitation>
. Famulus short, with small swelling distally. Solenidia simple.
</paragraph>
